<Name>Kimberly Campbell< /Name><user_id>104392037888370108405<//user_id><review>You Window Shoppe renewed my love affair with my house.  I literally am in love with my house again. It's probably not healthy that I am super obsessed with my new windows. Like, seriously. I refuse to put our blinds back up.

We've been wanting, err, needing new windows for years, but knew the price from most companies was way out of our range. But this year I decided we were going to take the plunge.  I contacted about 6 companies that I had found on yelp. Every single company quoted us between $2500 and $8000 MORE than Your Window Shoppe did. Say what?!?! You read that right.  I'll rephrase.  Your Window Shoppe was thousands more affordable. No, not cheaper... affordable. Why? They manufacture their windows and cut out the middle man, which is why other companies are so expensive.

From the moment I emailed them wanting to set up a quote, I was impressed by their customer service. Nick and Margie, the owners, really pride themselves in customer service. They were always quick to answer questions.  Nick is a no pressure guy. I can't even call him a sales guy. He just came, was friendly, answered all of our questions, showed us their product and took measurements to give us a quote.  All he asked from us was that we let him know once we got the quote. He didn't bug us for our business.

About 4 weeks after saying yes, the installers, Frank and Jacob, are amazing. They were on time everyday. Communicated with us throughout the entire process. They worked hard and quick, making sure to clean up as they go. They even worked with us to do our daughter's room first so we could get her down for a nap.  These guys were beyond professional. Every detail from install, to cleanup to the trim was amazing.  They protected my carpet and furniture as well.
I noticed a few small scratches on one of the windows (inside and out) and they are making a replacement for it. Easy peasy!

We recently used Your Window Shoppe to replace a kitchen window and sliding glass door.  The service they provide is outstanding! From start to finish the experience was undoubtedly the best purchase and installation service we've had as homeowners for 20+ years. The owners (Nick and Margie) are delightful to do business with and provide very competitive pricing and high quality products. When we visited their showroom, Nick also provided us a complete tour of their window factory explaining every step of the manufacturing process. The installation team was also top notch. Frank and his assistant completed the removal, installation, and clean-up flawlessly. Frank even asked what type/color caulking we preferred where the door frame mated with our tile floor. The finished installation is beautiful, and a complete joy to have a door and window that open smoothly and lock securely. We'll be using Your Window Shoppe again as we continue to replace our aluminum-framed windows. A few final comments. When I requested an online quote via their website, Nick promptly called me the next morning. Based on the measurements I provided, he gave me a ballpark estimate over the phone. After coming to our home to measure the window and door, Nick determined that the window was slightly smaller than what I measured. Based on his measurements, he said the price would be a little less than the verbal estimate he previously gave over the phone. They followed with a written quote via email that was actually less than the verbal estimate. When does that happen? Lastly, we do things on a budget. If you are looking for high quality products and service at a competitive price, look no further than Your Window Shoppe.< /Text>

<date>1579067004280< /date><text>Pro

It‚Äôs one stop shop. We used to get all our grocery from one stop. Price is comparative to other stores. Produce and dairy is fresh. They also sell fresh somosa and few other savories. I shopped here for over an year, almost every week.

Con

The staff are friendly, but also take things for granted. They run this rewards program that gives you 20$ credit after you hit a certain threshold. But when things go Hayward , say the system crashes - they would start over from beginning. To enroll for the program - you will need to write down some personal details on a sheet of paper. There is no clarity how the data will be handled later, or who uses it for what.

I once had a credit that they failed to honor since the system was reset due to the power outage. They knew me as regular customer, yet they failed to honor the credit. For me it was not about the 20$, but more about how they take things for granted. These kind of things are unacceptable in bigger stores , but it‚Äôs ok to happen in Indian store ?? I stopped going there ever since.

I‚Äôve given a poor rating due to my experience and disappointment.

If these kind of things are petty and does not matter, then the place is one stop grocery shop for you !<//text><GmapID>0x808e2d68973890ad:0x9fcf5ded4b947e66</GmapID>< username>

One of the primier dining spots in Eastern Sierra. Unmatched views of Mono Lake, and if you like bird watching while you have supper, this is your spot.

The two sisters that run this place clearly have done this as a labor of love. Hate to sound gushie, but this really is a 5-star restaurant.

And yes, the food is delicious< /Review>

<Resp>None</Resp><review>Lana and Debbie are two sisters that run the inn. They work very hard to deliver a great experience. The place is small and casual with panoramic views of Mono Lake and the mountains. The Inn is well cared for and tastefully decorated with locally influenced art and furnishings. The food is amazing. The braised bison short ribs and gnocchi was ridiculously good. They were good to my kids too and made them a plain pasta dish. The wine was outstanding and the desserts were amazing. All super fresh ingredients and great cooking. I would definitely go again.</review></record>

<user>104835459764685553316< /user><user_name>Thomas McAuliffe</user_name><Time>1431696334507<//Time><rate>5< /rate><Text>New owner since January 2015. Lana (the owner) is a delight and the food prepared by Chef Kenny is extraordinary. He prepared a delicious vegetarian meal for me even though it wasn't on the menu! My dinner mate said his pork chop was one of the best ever. The chef makes his own rubs and reductions and the results are excellent. Everyone raves about the restaurant at the gas station on 120 at 395 but the historic Mono Inn deserves  the same accolades, and the setting is 100 times nicer.

The restaurant itself is right above Mono Lake and the views from the dining room are spectacular. I love the interior design too. The building is owned by the descendants of famed photographer Ansel Adams. A stone fireplace anchors one wall, and huge windows provide the view. Classic Stickley furnishings in oak complete the romantic setting. Beer and wine bar, outdoor seating in season.

Highly recommended!</Text><pics>None< /pics>< Response>
None</Response>

<Review>We've now eaten here several times, after hiking nearby.  Have always been accommodated, even without reservations.  Since they have a small staff, promptness of seating & service is variable, but we've found it very friendly & capable.  The food is both unusual (game, for instance) and excellent.  The setting is gorgeous, especially if it's warm enough to sit outside and watch the changing light over Mono Lake and the antics of all the hummingbirds.<//Review>< pictures>

<username>Jeff Sullivan<//username><rating>5</rating>< Resp>
None< /Resp>
< pics>
None</pics>
<UserId.>107459220492917008623< /UserId.><Text>Every region a higher-end restaurant and for the Mono Basin, this is it.  In Lee Vining you have the choice between a coffee shop, a restaurant next door, a deli/grill, and the Mono Inn.  Each serves its role well and at the higher end, you can't beat eh Mono Inn for the food or the view.

As other reviewers have noted, arrive before sunset for a treat, as Mono Lake has consistently excellent sunsets.  That's particularly true on the evenings before, during or after a full moon night, as the moon rises close to the same time that sunset is underway.  There is outdoor patio seating you can really enjoy the view from on a mild summer evening.

In spite of the enthusiasm expressed for the restaurant, it's useful to note that there's a very nice bar as well, and the restaurant has an excellent wine list, the most extensive and well-selected in the area.  I tend to pick the wine I want to have first, then select a meal to match, and on my last visit I was pleasantly surprised to see a hard-to-find Sean Thackery Rhone-style blend on the wine list.  The price seemed reasonable compared to what you might pay for it in the Bay Area or Los Angeles area.  Being a bit of a wine fan, that will bring me back to a restaurant faster than also-excellent food.

The restaurant is only open during the spring through fall seasons when most people visit the area, so call ahead if you might be visiting outside of their open dates.  This place can be popular, so particularly on weekends you might want to arrive a little on the early side to avoid waiting to get seated.<//Text>< GmapID>

< review>
Pinecrest Campground is a wonderful place to swim, sail and to hike around one of the most beautiful lakes in California. If you have asthma, please be careful due to the poor air quality. Right now it is the smoke, from the fires, that is the problem. Over the last five years, I have had severe asthma attacks from the campfire smoke that hovers above the campground. If you don‚Äôt have asthma or a compromised immune system then you will be fine.< /review>

<UserId.>102411492085923355252</UserId.>< username>
J N<//username>
< Date>
1568512359519<//Date>
< rating>
5< /rating>
<review>Pinecrest campground has been our spot for 15 yrs now, we go once a year and stay for at least 5days, anything shorter is depriving your inner child of playtime. The sites are always clean at check in and the restrooms are maintained accordingly, be sure to report any unruly guests, we had too last time just to keep it clean, kids were having a wet toilet paper war in one of the RR. Remember you can't control the weather and you can't pick your neighbors, so enjoy the stay as best you can, do your research on peak visit/camping days, weather/ fire/road conditions. Check the website for rules and regulations. Cheers.</review>< Pics>

<Text>Pinecrest is great. Hiking around the lake takes about 2 hours. You can venture further up the mountain to Cleo's bath, where the snow run of feeds the lake. There's a good beach/swim area. Boats can be rented for cruising around. It's also great that there is a speed limit, so no wake boarding or water skiing keeps wakes and traffic low. Outdoor movie night is fun, ice cream from the store is a nightly ritual. Items at the store are a little expensive, but it's the only store for miles..... supply and demand....

Yes, this place is POPULAR, and during peak season is nearly impossible to get into last minute. You are allowed 2 vehicles and 2 tents per site, or 1 vehicle, 1 tent and a camper. With no more that 6 people per site. The reason it can seem over crowded is due to the HUGE tents, extra vehicles, and extra stuff that people bring. Certain sites are huge and can acomodate large tents, barbecues, multiple pop up canopy etc. Other sites are more confined and would be best for a couple do tents and 2 suv's. Leave your long bed deseil truck at home unless you get a site that can accommodate it! Book in advance, and ask how big the site is!< /Text><user_id>101004273531868284424< /user_id></record>

<gmap_id>0x8097483df59ccac9:0x828f7de149bc8193<//gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
<pictures>None</pictures><gmapID>0x8097483df59ccac9:0x828f7de149bc8193</gmapID><Rate>3< /Rate><time>1496020522274< /time><user_name>Ari Lehman</user_name>< UserId.>
109337180343199495740</UserId.>
<Text>We heard all about this campsite and wanted to give a try. For us it was a two year wait, last year we had to cancel our campsite booking due to bad weather. This year we finally made the trip during the 2017 memorial weekend. Yes, you do have to book these campsites at least 6 months in advance. There is no debate the lake area is really lovely and has some nice features with a general store complex, snack bar, movie theatre, beach access, boating and hiking options. However the other reviewers are correct about the crowds, lack of parking, close campsites, the rough campsite bathrooms (no showers), and the high noise levels. This is like camping in Yosemite at the height of summer in the fraction of the space. We recommend camping outside of the valley, staying in a remote cabin and just coming in for the day (6am-10pm for day parking). We are veteran campers and for us the night time noise was intense. We had at least three large groups in our area doing heavy partying with live music plus the sounds of the nearby open air movie theatre (D loop). We ended up leaving a day early just so we could get some rest, take a shower and escape from the noise. We would definitely come back in the future but we plan on sleeping elsewhere.</Text><resp>None</resp></record>
</dataset><record>

< Rate>
2< /Rate>
<text>The D loop of campsites was a bust for us.  The campsites are very densely packed and you end up feeling like you're right on top of other campers.  There's also little to no grass, and thus very dusty so be prepared for that.  Also, while it's nice to be so close to the lake in that you can walk to it that also means you're that much closer to the daytime hordes of people who come to hang out on the lakefront, particularly on weekends.  Some of these people see no problem in setting up their beach chairs and umbrellas right at the water's edge so that you are forced to literally walk through their stuff to actually get into the water.  The nicest part was being able to rent a 2-person kayak to go out on the lake and get away from the crowds for at least a little while.  The lake itself is certainly quite beautiful, so it's got that going for it.  Perhaps one of the other campsite loops (A, B, or C) would have been better, but I can definitely recommend avoiding loop D.</text><Pics>None</Pics><Resp>None<//Resp><gmap_id>0x8097483df59ccac9:0x828f7de149bc8193<//gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<Pictures>None<//Pictures><text>Great campground! So many pinetrees, great protection from the sun and wind. There is a general store that has absolutely EVERYTHING YOU NEED which is great if you forget an item or if a part in your RV breaks but, everything is super expensive at least double what you would pay at your local store. There is a restaurant, I didn't visit. And an amphitheater. The restrooms next to the amphitheater are airconditioned and automatic everything which is really nice. As for the other bathrooms they were clean, always had toilet paper, had mirrors, and not too many bugs. The lake is beautiful! The view of the mountains is breathtaking. <Text>One of my favorite places to go camping! If you love camping as much as I do, then you're constantly trying to get your skeptical friends (who have never gone camping and are scared of the idea to) to come with.

This is the best place to take new campers and then anyone who loves to swim in a lake. The water here can feel cold but it's not nearly as cold as Lake Tahoe. The campsites are not too crowded and everyone is really friendly. Facilites are cleaned frequently too which is nice.

Favorite Activities/Features of Pinecrest:
- Tent camping
- Outdoor movie theatre
- Boat/kayak/canoe rental
- Swimming
- Hiking

<user_id>113837164891822059043</user_id><Name>Mr. ‚ÄúMonkeys‚Äù Mrs.<//Name>< Time>
1548460776288</Time>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Review>
A good hidden secret is this street taco stand. They may not have all of the meat options one is used to, but they do have the usual ones.

Can't get "lengua" or chicken.

The tacos were great and so was the salsa...their horchata needed some work, though.

There isn't much in the service department, because you don't really deal with the people much, but their prices are great.

Overall, I would say this was a great experience, but expect to be standing because their are no tables. Otherwise, you can eat in your car...which may not be close by (their is only curb side parking and if there is no space near it, you will need to park around the corner and walk).</Review>

< text>
Fantastic customer service and value!

I reserved a climate controlled unit online (reserving online gets you a special discounted price) and received a call from Porche to finish setting up my unit. Everything was really easy, and with a couple of questions and DocuSign agreement (well, PactSafe actually, but same kind of thing) delivered through email I was all set up.

Pro tip: you can use your own renters‚Äô insurance policy and waive their coverage if you‚Äôd like. The one point in favor of their coverage is that there would be no deductible as opposed to typical renters policies. Do whatever makes sense in your situation depending on the value of your items and convenience to you and whatever other tradeoffs you need to consider.

The folks here are really professional and if you do stop by the office during business hours, everyone is wearing a mask, which is important to note during this COVID crisis.

To top it off, everything here is super clean. My unit is in their new building and it‚Äôs bright and spotless - really, really nice inside! Definite recommendation!< /text>

< text>
I just started storing some belongings at this facility. I am commenting on the process of getting a unit. I received 3 calls in two weeks about availability of units in a specific size I wanted. After deciding on their unit, they saved it for me (with a quote and first month free). I received a call in the morning stating it was still available and came in after work, it was mysteriously taken, price was raised, and first month was not free. I chose to not accept and left, they called 10-15 min later stating they made a mistake and I could have it in the quoted rate. Erich was kind enough to stay open later to get my paperwork finished and he even waved the admin fee. Besides the beginning process, nothing has been an issue. The unit was clean and cops were around every now and then! When moving out, all I had to do was let them know and took my lock off. A few days later, I received an email stating my unit was closed out! I would do business with them again.< /text>

<Time>1423019725227<//Time><user_name>Jeff Brown</user_name>< Review>
Storage unit was clean, accessing the facility was easy, and I had no issues with my month of usage. I will say, however, that I wish the folks running Extra Space Storage were not so pushy in regards to having customers review their business on Google. I was asked at my initial meeting to please review, to which I said I would -- I then received numerous emails over the span of a few weeks prompting me to please review the business. I understand you want to garner some positive feedback but I don't see the logic behind reviewing a business I have barely used. Now that I have emptied my unit I am more than willing to review the business, and they worked quite well, but the pushiness cost them a star.<//Review>

< text>
Such a nice walk down to the lake shore. It snowed while we were there. I would recommend crampons for inexperienced hikers during snowy months. I was fine hiking in Aria boots. There were ducks and geese in a smaller pool of water that walked straight over probably thinking we‚Äôd feed them. I will note that the public restrooms were closed and the portable restrooms were completely full.</text>

Beautiful home and beautiful spot. It's a steep hike on a very easy to walk on path. Small legs will probably need assistance. But it was worth the trek to see the beautiful sites and this beautiful home. There are picnic tables to have lunch and kayak rentals. The falls is breathtaking and would be a great day trip!< /Review>

<username>Ashneal Prasad<//username><GmapID>0x809986f8cb869efd:0xd79554c750511182<//GmapID><UserId.>116102271172681442509</UserId.>< Date>

< userid>
105431367601122882712< /userid>
< user_name>
Ken and Alicia Lund</user_name>
<date>1523850331030<//date><rating>5< /rating>< text>
Fascinating tour of a beautiful 1920s mansion built at the short of picturesque Emerald Bay in Lake Tahoe. Full of Scandinavian workmanship, building methods, design features, and art motifs, it is really a fascinating architectural marvel. The tour is informative. A one-mile hike is required to reach the home on foot--no car access. It is downhill down and all uphill back to the parking lot. Boat access is conceivable. Well worth a visit.</text>

< text>
Very cool Castle on the bank of Emerald Bay. We've always hiked there as it's gorgeous there.

They have a small visitor center where you can get food/drinks (snacks really) and bathrooms.

There's a nice beach as well.</text>

<Text>Beautiful hike, but keep in mind it is going back be a little taxing for those not in shape or if the weather is warm
Definitely should take some water with you.  If you forgot  the store at the bottom sell water and Gatorade (not always cold on hot days, sine since everyone is buy them when it is warm out). I have been told there is a longer trail back up, but we have yet to try it.

Tour is $15 which all goes back into keeping Vikingsholm maintained.

The beach in the summertime can get crowded early.
You can also rent kayaks and SUP by the hour with discounts for multiple hours. You can kayak over the island to see the Tea House.</Text>< pictures>

Emerald Bay area is just awesome. < Text>
Absolutely stunning home.  Emerald Bay is beautiful.  Breath taking.  Be aware if you want to visit this historical home...it cost $10 to park and is very hard to find parking there.  We had to park on the side of the highway about a half mile away.  Once you get to the trail head its about a mile down hill to the house and beach.  You know what that means, right?  It's a mile UP hill back.  With tired cranky children it can challenging.  Bring a stroller if you can.< /Text>

< username>
Josh Farnsworth<//username>
<Time>1564016344562<//Time><rate>3</rate>< text>
Pack water!!! No way in or out without a boat or hiking. There is a paved road but only state park employees and volunteers can drive it. The hike is 1.6 miles on the paved road (steep walk back) . The Rubicon trail from the state park is 1.7 miles on a Rocky, muddy, dirt trail with ups and downs. Its a nice hike if you are prepared for it. (We had sandals on so it wasn't very pleasant.) I think the state should allow a shuttle service to use the paved road. It would be a good way to earn money for the state parks. There is a very limited selection of cold drinks at the tiny shop (provided they keep it stocked up and cold- they use a mini fridge)</text>

<username>Natalie Ruvalcaba</username><time>1564700066936< /time>< rate>
3</rate>
< review>
Tickets were $15 per person for the "Mansion" and quite frankly it's really small. Not at all what we had imagined. Also, just so you know...you must hike down to get to this location from the top of Emerald Bay. There are some free parking spaces off the road but are very limited. Main parking is $10 for the day. The hike is pretty steep coming up. Do not recommend taking strollers. Road is rocking and space at beach is very limited. Perfect place for kayaking and paddleboarding.< /review>

1579567765630<//Date>
<rating>5</rating>< Review>
Vikingsholm is a great place to visit, offering beautiful architecture and a fascinating story behind its creation (no Viking colony on Lake Tahoe, sorry).

It seems like most people drive here but we arrived from the water, beaching the boat right in front of Vikingsholm during a day of exploring Emerald Bay and Fannette Island.

Make sure to bring your camera as you'll definitely want to take pictures of this place!</Review>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< review>
WOW....the views on the drive to Vikingsholm and the hike were incredible. Take the Vikingsholm tour (about $36 for a family of four) and learn some pretty cool history of the home and property surrounding the whole area. Make sure you complete your tour of Vikingsholm and then head to a simple but beautiful hike to Eagle Falls, which is just down a path from the castle.< /review>

<user_id>105306901194213777094< /user_id>< Name>
Margaret Darrow</Name>
<Date>1557884552840</Date><rating>5< /rating>< review>
Really nice hike down to the water, and the house is beautiful. The park service warns that the path is very steep, and while this is true it is much easier going down than it is coming back up, so be prepared for that. The hike back up to the parking lot is much harder because of the consistent grade, bring water and wear comfortable shoes. The house is only open for tours between memorial day and September 30th, but even if you can't go inside it's still worth a trip. The exterior architecture is very intricate, and there's no other buildings quite like this anywhere in the US that I know of.< /review>

< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< text>
Okay, this place will appeal to many people. Exercise enthusiasts (that mile climb back up is NO JOKE), but especially history buffs and fans of Scandinavian (Viking) design and artifacts. Not to mention it is on the drop dead gorgeous Emerald Bay beach. The hike up almost gave me a heart-attack, but I'd do again again anytime to see that house and lounge in the area. Next time I'm going in by boat, though...<//text>

<Time>1567637033102</Time><Rate>5</Rate><Review>Get there before 10:00 a.m. to make sure you get a parking spot unless you want to park along the road.  It's a mile walk down and a pretty steep walk up but it's all on relatively even surface.   They have a small gift shop at the bottom that has some ice cream and water.  There are also restrooms but no water in the restrooms.

The tour of Vikingsholm was 30 minutes long and a guide provided a brief history of the family and property.  You could look into the rooms but only were able to enter one.  Still, it was worth it to us and we enjoyed Inspiration Point, a hike up to Cascade Falls and a visit to Vikingsholm.< /Review>< pics>

< Text>
A bit of a step 1-mile hike down, but I made it while 24-weeks pregnant so you can too :-) The tour was very cool, every half hour, and got a close-up look at the rooms inside the home. The grounds afford a lovely view and access to Lake Tahoe, with a small beach area, picnic area, and access to kayak, paddle board/boat rentals for those who want to check out the Tea House on the island. Well worth a visit!<//Text>

Great hidden gem in Emerald Bay. Worth the walk down (and back up!). Restrooms at the bottom and amazing views. We didn‚Äôt tour the home since it‚Äôs offseason but worth going down even so.<//review>
</record></dataset><record>
< date>
1528217317734< /date>
<username>Gaby Michel< /username>< review>
Definitely worth the hike!! Unfortunately the options for anyone physically disabled are not good: my 80 year old grandma has trouble walking due to hip and back issues, and when she asked what the options were for a handicapped person she was told anyone who needs special assistance needs to call almost a month in advance to have a wheelchair ready, as there are none on sight. My grandma decided to tough it out and successfully made it down and up the hill! She was so happy to tour the home again, as this was her first trip to tahoe in 20 years. I hope we can bring the rest of our family back with us next year!<//review>

< name>
Sumit Sen<//name>
<Time>1583193292533< /Time><Rating>4<//Rating><Text>A nice 2 mile hike for families with moderate elevation.  The trail goes from a parking lot to the Vikingsholm mansion and beach.  It is partially shaded by tall pine trees and cliffs, and several streams cross under it at different points.  The house is closed in winter but is still worth visiting to see it from outside. It's a very unusual medieval-style Nordic mansion constructed around a courtyard and with a partial sod roof.  The beach is very inviting with some picnic benches and a pier.  The neighboring island can be visited by boat (in summer I presume) but you aren't allowed to swim there.</Text><pics>None</pics>< resp>

<review>Going back in time to feel the gentle calm in part of Tahoe history. The architecture is intriguing, beautiful, artistic, understated Norwegian Castle with it's modesty as opposed to palatial extravagance. So if you're expecting grandiose, save the trip, if you're looking for a melancholy walk back in time to learn a piece of history and love for the appreciation of natural beauty, it's a must see. The restrooms are provided but be warned, they're the pits! Literally!<//review>< pics>

< Text>
Although it was quite a hike to get to (especially on the way back up, 1 mile up hill) the staff were great, friendly and accommodating. It was worth it. Breathtaking views! Easy process and the equipment was reliable and easy to use. Make sure you leave some energy for thr hike back up hill! We (3 kids and i) rented one kayak and a paddle board for a full day. We arrived at 12p and brought it back at 5p. Exhausting but exhilarating!  Nice beach and peir was fun to jump off of! Water was beautiful...just like Hawaii...can see through to the bottom.<//Text>

I wish I could have gone inside but ...Covid-19 and 2020.</review>< GmapID>

Absolutely amazing! What a great way to spend a few hours. The trail down to Vikingsholm is nice and shaded with fantastic views. <rating>5< /rating><review>Beautiful old mansion based on Scandinavian architecture. Awesome layout. Beautiful river is close. It is a fairly long hike to get there (one mile) and the hike back isnt easy. Not rough, just steep. Stop and catch your breath. Plan your day so it isn't closed (inside) when you get there. And (paid) parking is limited so get there early. Hours were 10:30 to 4:30, seasonally for guided tour.  You might want to confirm. Kayak rental nearby. Pack water and snacks. Highly recommended!</review><pictures>None< /pictures><response>None< /response>< Gmap_id>

<name>Abz Lee< /name>< date>
1528779822957</date>
< pictures>
None< /pictures>
<gmap_id>0x809986f8cb869efd:0xd79554c750511182<//gmap_id>< text>
Beautiful Castle and beach! You have to park  at the top of the hill at an overlook which requires payment. Then, you hike down a steep trail quite a ways to the castle which lies next to the shore. The Castle was closed when I visited, but the outside views are absolutely gorgeous. (There are tours during summer which require payment as well.) You can see the island in the bay from the beach and walk around the castle. The nature and animals in the area were wonderful as well. There were geese on the beach, jays following us around the building and even a few chubby chipmunks hanging out along the path. The park ranger was friendly as well. Overall, the place was beautiful and welcoming. I highly recommend the hike to see it!</text>

< text>
Easy one mile walk to the beautiful house. Not a "castle" by any definition, but a stunning Scandinavian inspired house in an incredible location. House is closed through the winter until Memorial Day. Lower eagle falls is just past the house. Beach offers beautiful views of Emerald Bay and the tea house. Must see if in Lake Tahoe.<//text>

<user_id>106614229567752325323< /user_id><Name>Bill Burke</Name><time>1530508151696< /time>< Rating>
4<//Rating>
< Text>
Historic building,  if you enjoy California and lake tahoe history it is a nice tour.  There is a 1 mile walk to the lake and building.  Not bad going down. But going back up may be a struggle if you are not ready for it.  Some spots are steep and I saw a few groups really struggling. Carry your own water. It is not available at the bottom.
Parking is a problem.  The small lot ($10 charge) fills up early and you have to park on the highway and walk.  We got there at noon and had a 1/2 mile walk just to get to the trail.< /Text>

<Text>The Vikingsholm has a lot of typical Scandinavian details, which I have seen a lot during my trips to Norway and Sweden. There is a parking lot at the top, where you have to pay $10 for a day card. From there you walk down the path to the house where you will pass some beautiful pine trees. There is also a small beach and the Eagle waterfall comes out into the lake just a small walk after the house. A really nice stop when you are driving around the lake.</Text><pictures>None</pictures><Resp>None< /Resp>< Gmap_id>

<username>Mr M<//username><Date>1535330965472<//Date>< Rate>
4</Rate>
<Text>A quaint and very unique home/castle right on the shores of Emerald Bay.  You can get here by boat, kayak, hiking the Rubicon trail, or from the main road above (parking area day permit required) and then hike down on a somewhat steep but short trail.  Vikinsholm is available to see by buying a tour either at the next door visitor center or by purchasing one of the local guided boat tours.  Bring your camera, extra water, snacks, and swimsuits if you want to take a dip in the bay and spend a little time on the very small beaches.  Most people just wear their swimsuits and hike in. There is a restroom, but I don't think there was any running water.< /Text><Pics>None</Pics><Resp>None<//Resp>< GmapID>

< Text>
(Translated by Google) In the south of Lake Tahoe in Emerald Bay. Beautiful, people usually go in summer but calm atmosphere. If you leave soon you can take tables to eat there and areas near the water where you are.
Cold water for bathing but the children and the cheerful older bathe. Possibility of renting kayaks $ 25 / double hour.
It is ideal for a good day. On the weekend it must be crowded. In winter, snow.
There is no drinking water and you have to walk 2.5 km to get there. Parking at $ 10 above but you can leave the car in the access roads, be careful not to step on the white line with the wheels of the car.
There is a water jacket in the area before going down from the road to the lake.

(Original)

Agua fr√≠a para ba√±arse pero los ni√±os y los mayores alegres se ba√±an. Posibilidad de alquilar kayaks 25$/hora dobles.

Hay casaca fas de agua por la zona antes de bajar desde la carretera a las orillas del lago.</Text>

(Translated by Google) In the same lake Tahoe.
A wonderful place.
Leave your car on the road, to the side to avoid paying $ 10 for parking (very small). From the parking lot there is a road of 1.5 km approx. that goes down to the lake.
Crystal clear waters and large forest Ideal for children despite the walk.
There are signs that indicate the cold of its waters, but it is not so much, not much more than the water of the beaches of the Costa Brava.
I advise you to pass the beach and look for a more intimate corner.
There are picnic tables throughout the forest.
Next to it is a small waterfall.

(Original)
